@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Requirements" "What you need to run mftp"

@{u}Requirements@{uu}


@{b}Computer:@{ub}  Amiga 500 - 4000T or Draco

@{b}Memory@{ub}  :  When AmiTCP is already running, 150kB should be enough.

@{b}OS@{ub}      :  Kickstart 2.1 or better

@{b}Software@{ub}:  @{"AmiTCP 3.0" link "MUI AmiTCP"} or better (maybe 2.3 works too.. never tried it)
           © 1994 by Network Solution Development Inc, Finnland
             @{i}available on AmiNET or other sites.@{ui}

           @{"MUI 3.1" link "MUI AmiTCP"} or better
           © 1992-95 by Stefan Stunz, Germany
             @{i}available on AmiNET or other sites.@{ui}
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Installation" "How to install mftp"

@{u}Installation@{uu}


@{b}Install@{ub}:  Simply double click on the preferred language
          in the drawer "Install" and give the requested information.

@{b}CLI@{ub}    :  Copy the executable to a path of your choice.
           i.e.: @{i}copy mftp amitcp:@{ui}
                 @{i}copy mftp.info amitcp:@{ui}
          Copy the catalogfile to the according directory.
           i.e.: @{i}copy deutsch/mftp.catalog LOCALE:Catalogs/deutsch@{ui}

          If the file 'mftp.key' is included, copy it to 's:'

You can start mftp from CLI or Workbench... as you wish.
To be on the save side you should use a @{b}stack@{ub} size of
about 5000 Bytes. I think the maximum mftp uses is around 3000 Bytes.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Operation" "Help on operation"

@{u}Operation@{uu}


When you start mftp a window should appear which looks simmilar to this:

  @{"local path      " link "Local path"}@{"O" link "Local drive"}  @{" binary  " link "Transfer mode"}  @{"remote path     " link "Remote path"}@{"O" link "Remote history"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" -->     " link "Direction"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" toggle  " link "Toggle"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" parent  " link "Parent"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" refresh " link "Refresh"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" mkdir   " link "MkDir"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" copy    " link "Copy"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" move    " link "Move"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" rename  " link "Rename"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" delete  " link "Delete"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                  " link "Local list"}  @{" view    " link "View"}  @{"                  " link "Remote List"}
  @{"                                                   " link "FTP Output"}
  @{"                                                   " link "FTP Output"}
  @{"  Connect  " link "Connect"}@{"   Close   " link "Close"}@{"  Setup  " link "Setup"}@{"  About  " link "About"}@{"  Exit " link "Exit"}
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Local path" "Local path string gadget"

@{u}Local path string gadget@{uu}


 This string gadget contains the current directory of your computer.
 You can enter a path manually but usually this is not necessary.
 To its right you'll find a @{"popup gadget" link "Local drive"} which offers a list of available
 drives and assigns.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Local drive" "Local popup drive list"


@{u}Local popup drive list@{uu}


 If you click on this gadget a list which contains all available drives
 and assigns will popup. You can select one by simply clicking on a entry
 once.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Local list" "List of local files and directories"

@{u}List of local files and directories@{uu}


 This list contains the files and directories in the @{"current path" link "Local path"}
 on your local machine. Double click on a directory to enter it.
 If you double click on a file you start the filetransfer (only
 possible when @{"connected" link "Connect"}).
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Remote path" "Remote path string gadget"

@{u}Remote path string gadget@{uu}


 This string gadget contains the current directory of the remote computer.
 You can enter a path manually but usually this is not necessary.
 To its right you'll find a @{"popup gadget" link "Remote history"} which offers a list of the
 directories you've already been in during this session.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Remote history" "Remote popup history list"


@{u}Remote popup history list@{uu}


 If you click on this gadget a list which contains all the directories
 you already visited during the current session. It is a history list.
 You can select a directory by simply clicking on a entry once.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Remote list" "List of remote files and directories"

@{u}List of remote files and directories@{uu}


 This list contains the files and directories in the @{"current path" link "Remote path"}
 on the remote machine. Double click on a directory to enter it.
 If you double click on a file you start the filetransfer.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Transfer mode" "Cycle gadget: Transfer mode"

@{u}Cycle gadget: Transfer mode@{uu}


 This cycle gadget lets you choose the transfer mode.
 Available modes are:

 @{b}binary:@{ub}  No changes are made to the file.
          You will get a 1:1 copy. (mostly used)

 @{b}ascii :@{ub}  This mode is useful for transfering text files.
          Depending on the direction cr/lf are transformed to lf or
          vice versa.

 @{b}auto  :@{ub}  mftp will use the @{"ascii" link "ascii patterns"} and @{"binary" link "binary patterns"} pattern list to
          determine if binary or ascii mode should be used for a file.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Direction" "Direction of transfer/ Active list"

@{u}Direction of transfer/ Active list@{uu}


 This button lets you chose the active list. The buttons below this
 one have only effect on the list the arrow points @{b}away@{ub} from.
 The arrow also indicates the direction of the transfer for @{"copying" link "Copy"}
 or @{"moving" link "Move"} files.
 It changes its state automatically if you click on a file in the
 list which wasn't active.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Toggle" "Toggle file/directory selection in active list"

@{u}Toggle file/directory selection in active list@{uu}


 This toggles the selection of files and directories in
 the @{"active" link "Direction"} list. The ones which were
 selected become deselected and the other way around.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Parent" "Go to parent directory"

@{u}Go to parent directory@{uu}


 Change to the parent directory of the @{"active" link "Direction"} list
 and get its contents.
@EndNode
@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Refresh" "Refresh the active list"

@{u}Refresh the active list@{uu}


 Refresh the file/directory listing which is currently @{"active" link "Direction"}.
 If the right @{"(remote)" link "Remote List"} listing is active and the
 @{"directory caching" link "Directory caching"} is on, mftp will clear the directory's cache
 and  retrieve it from the remote host again.
@EndNode
@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "MkDir" "Create a directory"

@{u}Create a directory@{uu}


 Create a directory in the @{"active" link "Direction"} list.
 A requester will ask you for its name.
@EndNode
@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Copy" "Copy files"

@{u}Copy files@{uu}


 This copies all selected files in the @{"direction" link "Direction"} the arrow points.
 Only files will be copied; you can't copy directories.
@EndNode
@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Move" "Move files"

@{u}Move files@{uu}


 This moves all selected files in the @{"direction" link "Direction"} the arrow points.
 Only files will be moved; you can't move directories.
 The files at the source will be @{b}deleted@{ub} (only if the
 transfer was successful) !!
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Rename" "Rename files/directories"

@{u}Rename files/directories@{uu}


 Rename all selected files and directories in the @{"active" link "Direction"} list.
 A requester will ask you for each filename.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Delete" "Delete files or empty directories"

@{u}Delete files or empty directories@{uu}

 Delete all selected files and empty directories. You will be prompted
 if you really want to do this unless you didn't deselect @{"confirm delete" link "Confirm delete"}
 in the @{"setup" link "Setup"}.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "View" "View files"

@{u}View files@{uu}


 View the contents of the selected files. The default viewer is
 SYS:Utilities/More but you can override that if you set the
 environment variable @{b}PAGER@{ub} (env:PAGER) to the viewer of your
 choice. If you do so, you have to see to it that this viewer
 doesn't detach itself (i.e. -keepIO).
 Be careful if you select more than one file. mftp will start a
 separate process for each and this will popup as many viewers as
 files were selected.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "FTP Output" "FTP Output"

@{u}FTP Output@{uu}


 This is a list of the ftp output.
 You can change the @{"number of lines" link "History lines"} in the @{"setup" link "Setup"}.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Close" "Close connection"

@{u}Close connection@{uu}


 Close an already existing connection.
 This flushes the @{"directory cache" link "Directory caching"}.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "About" "Open the about requester"

@{u}Open the about requester@{uu}


Shows version information and address of the @{"author" link "Author"}.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Exit" "Terminate mftp"

@{u}Terminate mftp@{uu}


Closes an eventually existing connection and exits.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Connect" "Open connect requester"

@{u}Open connect requester@{uu}


 Opens a requester to enter data which will be used to connect
 to a remote host or adding one to the @{"host list" link "Host list"} (in @{"setup" link "Setup"}):

    @{" Hostname  " link "Hostname"}          A label for this host
    @{" Address   " link "Address"}          The name/address of the remote host
    @{" Username  " link "Username"}          The username you login with
    @{" Password  " link "Password"}          The according password
    @{" Account   " link "Account"}          Account name (usually not needed)
    @{" Directory " link "Directory"}          The desired directory to start
    @{" Anonymous " link "Anonymous"}          Login as anonymous user

 If you click on "@{b}Okay@{ub}" mftp will try to establish a conntection
 to the given host. A status display will appear and inform you
 about the progress and giving you also the ability to abort.
 If mftp is not able to get a connection it might take some time
 until it returns to normal operation. Although it appears like
 it crashed it didn't. It's only a timeout of about one or two
 minutes.
 "@{b}Abort@{ub}" will cancel the reqeuster without further action.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Hostname" "A label for this host"

@{u}A label for this host@{uu}


 If you use the connect requester only for establishing a
 connection this field is of no use.
 But, in the @{"setup" link "Setup"} it is possible to enter a list of hosts
 which can be recalled later by the popup gadget to the right.
 In combination with this list the field has the function of
 a label for the entry.

 Examples you could enter :

    Mike's computer (root)
    Mike's computer (mike)
    AmiNET at wustl
    AmiNET at eunet
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Address" "The name/address of the remote host"

@{u}The name/address of the remote host@{uu}


 In this field you have to enter the name or the IP-address
 of the host you wish to connect to.

 Examples:

    ftp.wustl.edu
    ftp.eunet.ch
    130.59.10.40
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Username" "Username to login with"

@{u}Username to login with@{uu}


 In case you're not going to login as anonymous user you have
 to enter the username you want to use.
 If you select @{"anonymous" link "Anonymous"} this field will become
 ghosted as mftp will user the username "anonymous" automatically.

 Exapmles:

    dolphin
    root
    guest
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Password" "Password to login with"

@{u}Password to login with@{uu}


 Here you have to enter the password which corresponds to the
 given @{"Username" link "Username"}. If you select @{"anonymous" link "Anonymous"}
 this field will become ghosted as mftp will use your @{"email address" link "email address"}
 as password automatically (has to be set in the @{"setup" link "Setup"}).
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Account" "Name of the account"

@{u}Name of the account@{uu}


 This field holds the name of your account. Usually you don't
 need to enter anything here as it's obsolete - mftp still
 supports it. 
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Directory" "The desired directory to start"

@{u}The desired directory to start@{uu}


 Enter the path of the directory you wish to be
 in after login. This is useful to jump to a
 directory that i.e. holds amiga files.

 Expamples:

    ~aminet
    /pub/software/amiga
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Anonymous" "Login as anonymous user"

@{u}Login as anonymous user@{uu}


 If you select this field @{"Username" link "Username"}, @{"Password" link "Password"} and @{"Account" link "Account"}
 will become ghosted and you will login as anonymous user.
 This way you don't have to enter the username "anonymous" and
 your email address as password. mftp will use the @{"email address" link "email address"}
 that was given in the @{"setup" link "Setup"} as password.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Setup" "Change the setup"

@{u}Change the setup@{uu}


 This opens a window which offers three different pages:

 @{b}General:@{ub}

        @{" email address    " link "email address"}         Enter your email address
        @{" Default transfer " link "Default transfer"}         Default transfer mode
        @{" Treat link as    " link "Treat link as"}         Way to treat links

        @{" Show ftp output   " link "Show ftp output"}        Opens a list with ftp output
        @{" Show hidden files " link "Show hidden files"}        Also show hidden files
        @{" Auto update       " link "Auto Update"}        Update directory contents automatically
        @{" Confirm delete    " link "Confirm delete"}        Popup a requester before deleting
        @{" Transfer bell     " link "Transfer bell"}        Does a DisplayBeep at the end of transfer
        @{" Directory caching " link "Directory caching"}        Enable Directory caching

        @{" Transfer buffer       " link "Transfer buffer"}    Set size of transfer buffer
        @{" History lines         " link "History lines"}    Number of lines in ftp output


 @{b}Hosts:@{ub}

        @{" List   " link "Host list"}    List of predefined hosts

        @{" Edit   " link "Edit"}    Edit selected host
        @{" New    " link "New"}    Add new host to list
        @{" Remove " link "Remove"}    Remove selected host
        @{" Up     " link "Up"}    Move selected host up
        @{" Down   " link "Down"}    Move selected host down
        @{" Sort   " link "Sort"}    Sort the list


 @{b}Auto Recon:@{ub}

        @{" Binary patterns " link "Binary patterns"}    List of file patterns for binary transfer
        @{" ASCII patterns  " link "ASCII patterns"}    List of file patterns for ASCII transfer

        @{" Edit   " link "Edit"}             Edit the selected entry
        @{" New    " link "New"}             Add a new pattern to according list
        @{" Remove " link "Remove"}             Remove the selected entry from the list



              @{"     Save     " link "Save"}     @{"     Use      " link "Use"}    @{"    Cancel    " link "Cancel"}
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Email address" "Enter your email address"

@{u}Enter your email address@{uu}


 Enter your email address here. It will be used as password
 when you login as @{"anonymous" link "Anonymous"} user.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Default transfer" "Default transfer mode"

@{u}Default transfer mode@{uu} (default: binary)


 Set which @{"transfer mode" link "Transfer mode"} you want to use when you start
 mftp the next time.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Treat link as" "Way to treat links"

@{u}Way to treat links@{uu} (default: automatic)


 Select wheter you want links on the remote host to be listed
 as files or directories.
 If you choose @{b}'auto'@{ub} mftp does a short query on the remote
 host for each link. Depending on the amount of links this can
 take some time. In this mode mftp is also able to determine the
 correct size of a link !
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Show ftp output" "Opens a list with ftp output"

@{u}Opens a list with ftp output@{uu} (default: off)


 If selected there appears a list in the main window which
 shows all the responses we get from the remote host.

 NOTE: If you use NTSC 600x200 you might want to deselect
       it so @{"MUI" link "MUI AmiTCP"} won't switch to a smaller, unreadable font.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Show hidden files" "Also show hidden files"

@{u}Also show hidden files@{uu} (default: off)


 If selected mftp tries to also get the hidden files from the
 remote system.

 This way you'd be able to see the files that start with a
 dot "." (Unix) or files that end with a ".info" (Amiga).
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Auto update" "Update directory contents automatically"

@{u}Update directory contents automatically@{uu} (default: on)


 If selected mftp always updates the listing when you change
 the directory on the remote host (should usually be @{b}on@{ub}).
 When deselected you have to do a manual @{"refresh" link "Refresh"} every time
 you change a directory or connect to a host.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Confirm delete" "Popup a requester before deleting"

@{u}Popup a requester before deleting@{uu} (default: on)

 If selected you must confirm everytime when you want to
 delete something. Otherwise every @{"delete" link "Delete"} will delete
 the files @{b}IMMEDIATELY@{ub} !!
 So be careful if it's not selected !
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Transfer bell" "Does a DisplayBeep at the end of transfer"

@{u}Does a DisplayBeep at the end of transfer@{uu} (default: on)


 Every time a transfer is complete mftp will do a
 DisplayBeep which will flash your screen or play
 a sound (as selected in your preferences/sound).
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Directory caching" "Enable Directory caching"

@{u}Enable Directory caching@{uu} (default: on)


 Enables directory caching. This way mftp doesn't need to
 get the entire file list from the remote host when you
 change to a to a directory you have previously been in.
 mftp uses a directory in 'T:' to save every directory.
 (If you run out of memory you might want to delete theese
 files - NOT the directory !! - because mftp doesn't check
 if there is enough room.
 The files will automatically be deleted if you close a
 connection.

   If enabled it speeds up changing directories a lot !
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Transfer buffer" "Set size of transfer buffer"

@{u}Set size of transfer buffer@{uu} (default: 32768)


 Set the size in bytes for the transfer buffer. It is used
 while receiving and sending files. If you think mftp
 accesses your disk too often while transferring, just
 enlarge the buffer.
 mftp will access the disk always when 'x' bytes are received.
 So be careful not to set a very high value. If you receive a
 file and the transfer fails you loose the data that hasn't
 been written yet.

 Approx. 32 kB is a reasonble value here for dialup connections.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "History lines" "Number of lines in ftp output"

@{u}Number of lines in ftp output@{uu} (default: 50)


 Set the amount of lines which will be displayed in the
 @{"ftp output" link "ftp output"} list. If you're short with memory I suggest
 not to use a value higher than 50.

 NOTE: mftp will write the lines even if you switched
       off the @{"ftp output" link "ftp output"} and therefore this value
       still determines the memmory usage.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Host list" "List of predefined hosts"

@{u}List of predefined hosts@{uu}


 With this list you can predefine hosts which will be
 easily accessible in the @{"connect requester" link "Connect"} later (in the
 popup list).
 A double click on an existing entry has the same effect
 as @{"Edit" link "Edit"}.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Edit" "Edit selected entry"

@{u}Edit selected entry@{uu}


 "Edit" will open a requester where you can edit the
 currently selected entry.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "New" "Add new entry to list"

@{u}Add new entry to list@{uu}


 This will add a new entry to the list and let you
 enter the required data in a requester which pops up.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Remove" "Remove selected entry"

@{u}Remove selected entry@{uu}


 This removes the selected entry from the list.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Up" "Move entry up"

@{u}Move entry up@{uu}


 Move the selected entry on step upwards in
 the list.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Down" "Move entry down"

@{u}Move entry down@{uu}


 Move the selected entry on step downwards in
 the list.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Sort" "Sort the list"

@{u}Sort the list@{uu}


 Sort the list alphabetically.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Binary patterns" "List of file patterns for binary transfer"

@{u}List of file patterns for binary transfer@{uu}


 Here you can specify a list of file patterns which will
 be used to determine if mftp uses binary mode to transfer
 a file (in case "auto" is selected as @{"transfer mode" link "transfer mode"}).
 Standard amiga filepatterns are recognized.

 Examples:

    *.lha
    *.lzh
    *.zip
    *.exe

 NOTE: If a filename would match a pattern in the binary
       list @{b}and@{ub} the ascii list mftp will use ascii
       mode !!
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "ASCII patterns" "List of file patterns for ASCII transfer"

@{u}List of file patterns for ASCII transfer@{uu}


 Here you can specify a list of file patterns which will
 be used to determine if mftp uses ASCII mode to transfer
 a file (in case "auto" is selected as @{"transfer mode" link "transfer mode"}).
 Standard amiga filepatterns are recognized.

 Examples:

    *.txt
    *readme
    *.doc

 NOTE: If mftp can't find a match in this list it will
       use binary mode.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Save" "Save the setup"

@{u}Save the setup@{uu}


 This will save the setup permanently (to envarc:mftp.config).
 The @{"current directory" link "Local path"} on the local machine (yours) will also
 be saved so the next time you start mftp you are back in your
 donload directory or whatever you wish.
 If you changed the size of the @{"transfer buffer" link "Transfer buffer"} mftp tries to
 allocate the memmory.

 NOTE: It is not mftp's job to save the properties of the windows.
       Please refer to the @{"MUI" link "MUI AmiTCP"} manual on how to acomplish that.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Use" "Use the setup"

@{u}Use the setup@{uu}


 This will save the setup to env:mftp.config only.
 So if you perform a reset the changes will be lost.

 NOTE: If you changed the size of the @{"transfer buffer" link "Transfer buffer"}
       mftp tries to allocate the memmory.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Cancel" "Cancel all changes"

@{u}Cancel all changes@{uu}


 If you select "cancel" the setup will not be saved
 in any way and mftp reloads the last @{"used" link "Use"} or @{"saved" link "Save"}
 configuration (env:mftp.config).
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "ToDo" "What is still not implemented"

@{u}What is still not implemented@{uu}


* full AREXX support & Docs

* copy directories recursively

* proxy server support

* enter ftp commands manually

* Logfile :
     6 dec 1995 16:59:02 Start mFTP session (version 2.0)
     6 dec 1995 17:00:00 Connected to ftp.luth.se
     6 dec 1995 17:01:12 get /pub/amiga/comm/tcp/mFTP.lha (avg. 1300 cps)
     6 dec 1995 17.03.38 close connection   

* Drag and drop 

* automatc refresh after x minutes inactivity => no timeout.

* "Add to hotlist" button in connect requester. 

* localise bubble help

* automatc uuencoding/uudecoding

If you have any suggestions what else could be included, please @{"email" link "Author"} me !
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Bugs" "Known Bugs"

@{u}Known Bugs@{uu}


There several small bugs which should be corrected but
I won't try to find them because they won't be here
anymore in mftp II.
Please have a bit patience until mftp II appears.
@EndNode

@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Updates" "Where to find updates of mftp"

@{u}Where to find updates of mftp@{uu}


Updates of mftp can be found on aminet/comm/tcp/ and via

@{b}http://www.unizh.ch/~dolphin/mftp@{ub} 

On the web pages you'll find updates and bug corrections more
likely than on AmiNET. AmiNET will only contain major releases.
@EndNode

